The paper deals with optimization techniques for route planning in road networks, which involves algorithms and data structures for efficient processing of shortest path queries. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category. Additionally, the paper mentions that the objective to be optimized may change between every shortest path query, which implies that the paper may also be relevant to the cs.RO (Robotics) sub-category, as route planning is a common problem in robotics. The paper also discusses optimizations based on the topological structure of networks, which suggests that it may be relevant to the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-category, as this is a common approach in AI for solving optimization problems. The paper also presents experimental results on real-world road networks, which suggests that it may be relevant to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category, as machine learning techniques are often used for analyzing and processing large datasets. Finally, the paper may also be relevant to the cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) sub-category, as road networks can be seen as a type of social network and the techniques presented in the paper may be applicable to other types of networks as well.
